Employee Transportation Mode Prediction

R Markdown

This project is about predicting what mode of transport employees prefers to commute to their office. The dataset Cars-dataset includes employee information about their mode of transport as well as their personal and professional details like age, salary, work exp. The goal of this project is to predict whether or not an employee will use Car as a mode of transport. Also, which variables are a significant predictor behind this decision.

Inferences from the EDA

Although most of the details from the above report are self explanatory, here are som e of the important ones

  1. Variables Salary, MBA, Work.Exp, license are highly skewed

  2. From the correlation plot, it is seen that Age is highly correlated to Work Exp and Salary

  3. The dataset is highly imbalanced. Special techniques may be needed to balance the dataset if the models show signs of high variance

Bivariate analysis with Target variable

  1. Two wheeler and bike is famous mode of transporation among yonger people (20-30 years) and car is preferred option for people older than 30

  2. People travelling longer distances prefer car

  3. People without license are preferring public transport

The challenging part of this dataset are the imbalance dataset. Oversampling techniques like SMOTE can be used in the analysis to balance the dataset. SMOTE with undersampling is not preferred as the dataset has only 487 observations which is less

Another challenging part is the correlations between variables. Depending on the model performance, there are chances to drop few correlated columns and also consider performing PCA.

# Setting random seed to reproduce the same results everytime
set.seed(123)
library(caTools)
raw_data$MBA<-as.factor(raw_data$MBA)
#Creating dummy variables for factor column Gender
library(dummies)
## dummies-1.5.6 provided by Decision Patterns
raw_data<-dummy.data.frame(raw_data, names = 'Gender', omit.constants=TRUE)
#Standardisi ng numeric columns
library(BBmisc)
## 
## Attaching package: 'BBmisc'
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     isFALSE
num_columns <- subset(raw_data, select=c(Age,Work.Exp,Salary,Distance))
fact_columns <- subset(raw_data, select=-c(Age,Work.Exp,Salary,Distance))
scaled_columns <- normalize(num_columns, method = "range", range = c(0, 10), margin = 1L, on.constant = "quiet")
raw_data.scaled <- cbind(scaled_columns,fact_columns)
#Splitting the dev and validation data sets 70-30 ratio
sample = sample.split(raw_data.scaled,SplitRatio = 0.7)
dev <- subset(raw_data,sample == TRUE)
val <- subset(raw_data,sample == FALSE)
#Naive Bayes
library(e1071)

nb_gd<-naiveBayes(x=dev[,1:9], y=as.factor(dev[,10]))
#do make sure that your dependent variable is a factor

pred_nb<-predict(nb_gd,newdata = val[,1:9])

table(val[,10],pred_nb)
##                   pred_nb
##                    2Wheeler Car Public Transport
##   2Wheeler                9   0               15
##   Car                     0  12                0
##   Public Transport        9   1               79
paste("Accuracy: ",mean(pred_nb == val$Transport))
## [1] "Accuracy:  0.8"

Interpretation of Naive Bayes

The accuracy of the model is 80%, which looks like a good number. However, upon inspection of the matrix, it is evident that the model is poorly predicting the 2Wheeler. Car category is predicted perfectly but the other two categories are not as accurate and the reason I can imagine is because of highly correlated variables. Age and Experience are two variables which have equal amount of impact on the output and hence, the results. Public Transport is predicted better than the 2Wheeler may be because of the difference in the number of observation

#knn compare
library(class)
knn_fit<- knn(train = dev[,1:9], test = val[,1:9], cl= dev[,10],k = 3)
#here were have predicted the  minority class all wrong. But we still do have a high probability of being correct.
#Is it a good model though?

table(val[,10],knn_fit)

## Residual Deviance: 226.5844 
## AIC: 262.5844
logit_preds<-predict(log_reg,val[,1:9])

Interpretation of Multinom

This model perfoms differently than the KNN and Naive Bayes Public Transport is predicted well than the other 2 classes is because of the number of observations.

#Bagging
library(ipred)
library(rpart)
bag<-bagging(Transport~.,data = dev, control=rpart.control(maxdepth=15, minsplit=30,minbucket = 3,xval = 13 ))

table(val$Transport,bag_preds)
##                   bag_preds

##   Public Transport        4   1               84

  n.trees = 1000,

  shrinkage = 0.001,
  cv.folds = 5,
  n.cores = NULL, 
  verbose = FALSE
)

Conclusion

Overall, the model accurariesof all models looks similar but boosting has higher accuraries by a small margin. The dataset has very small number of observations, high correlated variables and a class imbalance. Accuracy can be improved by tackling the correlation and class imbalance.
